<li> <a href="?cover=print#Prerequisite"> Prerequisite </a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Using_an_HTTP_Proxy"> Using an HTTP Proxy</a> <ul>
<li> <a href="?cover=print#Staging_Files"> Staging Files</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Finding_an_HTTP_Proxy"> Finding an HTTP Proxy</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Using_an_HTTP_Proxy_AN1"> Using an HTTP Proxy</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Stage_a_whole_database"> Stage a whole database</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Using_HTTP_Securely"> Using HTTP Securely</a>
</li></ul> 
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Caching_and_BLAST"> Caching and BLAST</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Remote_I_O"> Remote I/O</a>
</li></ul> 
</li></ul> 
</div>
In Exercise set 3, we improved the scalability of our BLAST runs by first staging the data to an OSG SE.  This achieved our goals, but required substantial manual work to move the data across the grid.
<p />
In this set of exercises, we will try a different approach: caching.  We will stage the data to one HTTP server, and rely on the site's HTTP caches to bring the data closer to the running job, and provide scalability.
<p />
<h1><a name="Customize_this_document"></a> Customize this document </h1>
